Date: Fri, 31 Jul 1998 08:57:08 -0400
From: Gerald L. McLaughlin, Ph.D <gmclaugh@iupui.edu>

The symptoms seem fairly non-specific; I'll admit to favoring excessive
broad-ranging clinical diagnostics. If insurance would pay or you have
spare resources, a few other infectious disease rule-outs while checking
for heavy metal poisoning could be done, like:
-Giardiasis, other intestinal protozoa (O&P exam); some travel
-Toxoplasmosis, trichinellosis, tissue parasites
-Hantavirus from rodent urine or feces; outdoors type, garage clean-up?
-Anisaka/Phoconema nematode gut helminths; from Sushi
-Fungal infections from nitrate-rich soils (e.g. bird/bat fecal
contamination), perhaps _Histoplasma_ (within wbc); _Coccidioides_,
_Pneumocystis_ (lung lavages)...
-Babesiosis or malaria (intraerythrocytic protists; blood smear stain)
-High-titer viruses (CMV, EBV, Herpes virus, parvovirus...)
-Obscure bacteria (_Chlamydia pneumoniae_, _Bartonella hensliae_)
--
